## **Deploy Kubernetes cluster in ubuntu 22.04**

This document provides a step-by-step guide to configure a Kubernetes cluster in ubantu.

---

### **Prerequisites**
- Server is deployed with Ubuntu 22.04
- All the nodes are accessible with their respective names
- UFW disabled or all the required ports opened for managing UFW.

---

### **Installing Containerd, Kubectl, And Kubeadm Packages**

After doing the above-mentioned process, we have to install some packages on our machines. These packages are:

- **kubeadm** – a CLI tool that will install and configure the various components of a cluster in a standard way.
- **kubelet** – a system service/program that runs on all nodes and handles node-level operations.
- **kubectl** – a CLI tool used for issuing commands to the cluster through its API Server.
---
### **Deployment Steps**

In order to install these packages, follow the steps mentioned below on **Master as well as Worker nodes**:

**Step 1)** Disabled `SWAP`
```bash
swapoff -a
```
```bash
sed -i '/ swap / s/^\(.*\)$/#\1/g' /etc/fstab
```
**Step 2)** Configure persistent loading of modules.
```bash
tee /etc/modules-load.d/

containerd.conf <<EOF

overlay

br_netfilter

EOF
```
![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Step 3)** Load at runtime
```bash
modprobe overlay
```
```bash
modprobe br_netfilter
```
![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Step 4)** Update `Iptables Settings`
```bash
tee /etc/sysctl.d/kubernetes.conf<<EOF

net.bridge.bridge-nf-call-ip6tables = 1

net.bridge.bridge-nf-call-iptables = 1

net.ipv4.ip_forward = 1

EOF
```
![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Step 5)** Applying Kernel Settings Without Reboot
```bash
 sysctl --system
```
![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Step 6)** Adding Docker Repository GPG Key to Trusted Keys, so it allows the system to verify the integrity of the downloaded `Docker packages.`
```bash
 mkdir -m 0755 -p /etc/apt/keyrings
```
```bash
 curl -fsSL <https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg> | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg
```
![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Step 7)** Adding `Docker Repository` to Ubuntu Package Sources to enable the system to download and install Docker packages from the specified repository.

(**Note:** The below is a single command. Please copy and paste the command into a notepad first, then execute it.)
```bash
echo \
"deb [arch=$(dpkg --print-architecture) signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg] https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu \
$(lsb_release -cs) stable" | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list > /dev/null
```
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**

**Step 8)** Install `containerd.`
```bash
 apt-get update && apt-get install -y containerd.io
```
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**

**Step 9)** Configure containerd for Systemd `Cgroup Management` to `enable` the use of systemd for managing cgroups in containerd.
```bash
mkdir -p /etc/containerd**$(lsb_release -cs) stable" | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list > /dev/null**
```
```bash
containerd config default>/etc/containerd/config.toml
```
```bash
sed -e 's/SystemdCgroup = false/SystemdCgroup = true/g' -i /etc/containerd/config.toml
```
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**

**Step 10)** `Reloading Daemon`, `Restarting`, `Enabling`, and Checking containerd Service Status
```bash
systemctl daemon-reload
```
```bash
systemctl restart containerd
```
```bash
systemctl enable containerd
```
```bash
systemctl status containerd
```
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**

**Step 11)** Update the apt package index and install packages needed to use the **Kubernetes https certificate configuration.**
```
apt-get update && apt-get install -y apt-transport-https ca-certificates curl
```  
![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Step 12)** Add the Kubernetes Repository to System’s Package Sources.

This command adds the Kubernetes repository to the system’s list of package sources by appending the repository information to the file.
```bash
 echo "deb \[signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/kubernetes-apt-keyring.gpg\] <https://pkgs.k8s.io/core:/stable:/v1.28/deb/> /" | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/kubernetes.list**
```
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**

**Step 13)** Download the GPG key, as it is used to verify `Kubernetes packages` from the Kubernetes package repository, and store it in the kubernetes-apt-keyring.gpg file in the **/etc/apt/keyrings/** directory.
```bash
curl -fsSL <https://pkgs.k8s.io/core:/stable:/v1.28/deb/Release.key> | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/kubernetes-apt-keyring.gpg
```
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**
```bash
 sudo apt-get update
```
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**

**Step 14)** Install `kubelet`, `kubeadm`, `kubectl` packages.
```bash
apt-get install -y kubelet kubeadm kubectl
```
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**

**Step 15)** To hold the installed packages at their installed `versions`, use the following command.  
```bash
apt-mark hold kubelet kubeadm kubectl
 ```
 ![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Step 16)** Start the `kubelet` service is required on all the nodes.
```bash
systemctl enable kubelet
```
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**

**`(upto here do the same config for both the master and worker node)`**

## **Create a Kubernetes Cluster**

As we have successfully installed Kubeadm, next we will create a Kubernetes cluster using the following mentioned steps:

**Step 1)** We have to initialize kubeadm on the master node. This command will check against the node that we have all the required **dependencies**. If it is passed, then it will install control plane components.  
**(Note: Run this command in Master Node only.)**
```bash
 kubeadm init
```
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**

You will see a similar output:

**![](data:image/png;base64,)**

If cluster initialization has succeeded, then we will see a cluster join command. This command will be used by the worker nodes to join the Kubernetes cluster, so copy this command and save it for future use.

**Step 2)** To start using the cluster, we have to set the `environment variable` on the `master node`.

To start using your cluster, you need to run the following as a **regular user:**
```bash
mkdir -p $HOME/.kube
```
```bash
sudo cp -i /etc/kubernetes/admin.conf $HOME/.kube/config
```
```bash
sudo chown $(id -u):$(id -g) $HOME/.kube/config**
```
Alternatively, if you are the **root user**, you can run:
```bash
export KUBECONFIG=/etc/kubernetes/admin.conf**
```
```bash
echo 'export KUBECONFIG=/etc/kubernetes/admin.conf' >> .bashrc
```

**![](data:image/png;base64,)**

**![](data:image/png;base64,)  
### Join Worker Nodes to the Kubernetes Cluster

Now our Kubernetes master node is set up, we should join Worker nodes to our cluster. Perform the following same steps on all of the worker nodes:

**Step 1)** `SSH` into the Worker node with the username and password.
```bash
ssh <external ip of worker node>
 ```
 (**follow all the step we mention docs upword for worker node**)

**Step 2)** Run the kubeadm join command that we have received and saved.

**Note:** This command is specific to the cluster. Please use the command provided in your cluster instead of this one.
```bash
kubeadm join 10.210.102.2:6443 --token clrjtc.31s4ulsev7wlstpt \
--discovery-token-ca-cert-hash sha256:e86459d14f890db6fcf5d44c34b4dccce57dd00a9f931c54b8d999f6ccbd352e
```

**(Note:** Don’t use this same command, use the command that you have received and saved while doing `kubeadm` init command)  
<br/>**Note:** If you have forgotten to save the above received `kubeadm` join command, then you can create a **new token** and use it for **joining worker nodes to the cluster**.
```bash
kubeadm token create --print-join-command
```
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**

## **Testing the Kubernetes Cluster**

After creating the cluster and joining worker nodes, we have to make sure that everything is working properly. To see and verify the cluster status, we can use kubectl command on the master node:

Using **Kubectl get nodes** command, we can see the status of our `Nodes` (`master` and `worker`) whether they are ready or not.
```bash
kubectl get nodes
```
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**

We have to install `CNI` so that pods can communicate across nodes and also Cluster DNS to start functioning. Apply Weave `CNI`**(Container Network Interface)** on the master node.

```bash
kubectl apply -f	https://github.com/weaveworks/weave/releases/download/v2.8.1/weave-daemonset-k8s.yaml
```
![](data:image/png;base64,)  
Wait for a few minutes and verify the cluster status by executing `kubectl` command on the master node and see that nodes come to the ready state.
```bash
 kubectl get nodes
 ```  
<br/>![](data:image/png;base64,)

To verify the status of the system pods like coreDNS, weave-net, Kube-proxy, and all other `master node` system processes, use the following command:
```bash
 kubectl get pods -n kube-system
```
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**

Your output should match with the shown output above. If not, you will have to check whether you have performed all the steps correctly and on the mentioned node only.
